On July 9, 2009, the White House sent several nominations to the Senate. Some of the nominations included Rolena Klahn Adorno to be a member of the National Council on the Humanities, Craig Becker to be a member of the National Labor Relations Board, Christopher P. Bertram to be an Assistant Secretary of Transportation, and Francis S. Collins to be Director of the National Institutes of Health. Other nominations included Sherry Glied to be an Assistant Secretary of Health and Human Services, Brian Hayes to be a member of the National Labor Relations Board, James A. Leach to be Chairperson of the National Endowment for the Humanities, Philip D. Murphy to be Ambassador to Germany, and Mark Gaston Pearce to be a member of the National Labor Relations Board.